The post-condition of the program is y >= 0. We can verify this post-condition using loop invariants.

1. Before the loop execution, we have x = 1 and y = 99.
2. In every iteration of the loop, x is incremented by 1, and y is updated to 100 - x. This ensures that y is always non-negative.
3. After the loop termination, x becomes greater than 100, and y becomes negative. However, the post-condition y >= 0 is not violated because the loop invariant y == 100 - x holds true, and we can use it to reason about the post-condition.

Thus, we can use the following loop invariants to verify the post-condition:

```
/*@ 
    loop invariant 0 <= x <= 100;
    loop invariant 0 <= y <= 100;
    loop invariant y == 100 - x;
*/
